	for(initial value;condition;change criteria)
e.g.
all of the following loops will run for 20 times

    for (int i=0;i&lt;20;i++){
    	//Some logic
    }
    
    for (int i=1;i&lt;=20;i++){
    	//Some logic
    }
    
    for (int i=1;i&lt;21;i++){
    	//Some logic
    }
    
    for (int i=0;i&lt;=19;i++){
    	//Some logic
    }
    
    //Start i with 2 and increase it by 2 after every iteration until it reaches 40
    for (int i=2;i&lt;=40;i+=2){
    	//Some logic
    }
    
    //Start i with 20 and decrease it by 1 after every iteration until it reaches 1
    for (int i=20;i&gt;0;i--){
    	//Some logic
    }
    
    //Start i with 40 and decrease it by 2 after every iteration until it reaches 2
    for (int i=40;i&gt;=2;i-=2){
    	//Some logic
    }

...and so on. There can be infinite number of ways in which you can do it.

First of all, you haven&#39;t used nested `if` in your question at all. Nested `if` has the following structure (i.e. `if` inside `if`) which you do not have:

    if (condition1) 
    {
       // Executes when condition1 is true
       if (condition2) 
       {
          // Executes when condition2 is true
       }
    }

If you meant to get rid of multiple if&#39;s, you can use ternary operator but your code will look clumsy. Another alternative of if...else is switch...case but it won&#39;t fit with your question. If you are interested to explore more, you can check some other alternatives at baeldung.com/java-replace-if-statements 

